events.description: Portuguese explorer Pedro Alvarez Cabral reaches new coastline (Brazil).

events.description: Battle of Villalar: King Charles I of Spain defeats the Comuneros.
events.html: • 1521 – Battle of Villalar: King Charles I of Spain defeats the Comuneros.

events.description: The first public school in the United States, the Boston Latin School, is founded.
events.html: • 1635 – The first public school in the United States, the Boston Latin School, is founded.

events.description: The Siege of Santo Domingo begins during the Anglo-Spanish War, and fails seven days later.
events.html: • 1655 – The Siege of Santo Domingo begins during the Anglo-Spanish War, and fails seven days later.

events.description: Treaty of Oliva is established between Sweden and Poland.
events.html: • 1660 – Treaty of Oliva is established between Sweden and Poland.

events.description: King Charles II of England, Scotland and Ireland is crowned in Westminster Abbey.
events.html: • 1661 – King Charles II of England, Scotland and Ireland is crowned in Westminster Abbey.[3]

events.description: Johann Sebastian Bach leads the first performance of his cantata Du Hirte Israel, höre, BWV 104, illustrating the topic of the Good Shepherd in pastoral music.
events.html: • 1724 – Johann Sebastian Bach leads the first performance of his cantata Du Hirte Israel, höre, BWV 104, illustrating the topic of the Good Shepherd in pastoral music.[4]

events.description: The Second Serbian Uprising: A second phase of the national revolution of the Serbs against the Ottoman Empire, erupts shortly after the annexation of the country to the Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1815 – The Second Serbian Uprising: A second phase of the national revolution of the Serbs against the Ottoman Empire, erupts shortly after the annexation of the country to the Ottoman Empire.

events.description: Fire burns down the second main building and dome of the University of Notre Dame, which prompts the construction of the third, and current, Main Building with its golden dome.
events.html: • 1879 – Fire burns down the second main building and dome of the University of Notre Dame, which prompts the construction of the third, and current, Main Building with its golden dome.

events.description: Chilean Civil War: The ironclad Blanco Encalada is sunk at Caldera Bay by torpedo boats.
events.html: • 1891 – Chilean Civil War: The ironclad Blanco Encalada is sunk at Caldera Bay by torpedo boats.[5][6]

events.description: World War I: The British Royal Navy makes a raid in an attempt to neutralise the Belgian port of Bruges-Zeebrugge.
events.html: • 1918 – World War I: The British Royal Navy makes a raid in an attempt to neutralise the Belgian port of Bruges-Zeebrugge.

events.description: The Estonian Constituent Assembly is held in Estonia, which marks the birth of the Estonian Parliament, the Riigikogu.
events.html: • 1919 – The Estonian Constituent Assembly is held in Estonia, which marks the birth of the Estonian Parliament, the Riigikogu.[7]

events.description: The Grand National Assembly of Turkey (TBMM) is founded in Ankara. The assembly denounces the government of Sultan Mehmed VI and announces the preparation of a temporary constitution.
events.html: • 1920 – The Grand National Assembly of Turkey (TBMM) is founded in Ankara. The assembly denounces the government of Sultan Mehmed VI and announces the preparation of a temporary constitution.

events.description: Cardiff City defeat Arsenal in the FA Cup Final, the only time it has been won by a team not based in England.
events.html: • 1927 – Cardiff City defeat Arsenal in the FA Cup Final, the only time it has been won by a team not based in England.

events.description: The Polish Constitution of 1935 is adopted.

events.description: The Rhythm Club fire at a dance hall in Natchez, Mississippi, kills 198 people.
events.html: • 1940 – The Rhythm Club fire at a dance hall in Natchez, Mississippi, kills 198 people.

events.description: World War II: The Greek government and King George II evacuate Athens before the invading Wehrmacht.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: The Greek government and King George II evacuate Athens before the invading Wehrmacht.

events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Baedeker Blitz: German bombers hit Exeter, Bath and York in retaliation for the British raid on Lübeck.

events.description: World War II: Adolf Hitler's designated successor, Hermann Göring, sends him a telegram asking permission to take leadership of Nazi Germany. Martin Bormann and Joseph Goebbels advise Göring that the telegram is treasonous.
